{"Q0":"I was surprised at how difficult it seemed to be to weigh which of the two videos seemed to be from an actual responder, and only really came up with a strategy on how to do so by the fifth set of videos - at this point, I began tracing the path of the eye to see whether the movements made appeared realistic, rather than focusing on the amount of time spent on the content of the image (unless the content pathway was something attention-catching like text or faces)."}

{"Q0":"As stated in my prior response, I started out by focusing heavily on the amount of time spent looking at certain hotspots on screen, especially those I felt a human observer would pay more attention to. However, I soon realized that paying attention to the pathway of the eye and the way the eye switched from spot to spot was more distinguishing, and used those features to generate more confident results. Personally, I found that images which used a wide range of space for the eye to roam in focus points were far easier than images where the focus points were tightly clustered, a difficulty gradient that existed for both of my strategies."}

{"Q0":"As stated previously, images with clustered focus points or a small number of focus points threw me off, and I often felt I had very little time to get a sense of the agent's attentive movements or the content of the picture before it was time for me to make a comparison."}
